by New Anderia » Wed Apr 14, 2021 2:02 pm

I'm not sure which is a bigger NS cliché, societies that are bigotry-blind or societies that turn the bigotry up to 11 (usually for no good reason). There are also ones that are pretty much indistinguishable from modern countries in terms of diversity (or lack thereof).

I tend to want to go somewhere between bigotry-blind and indistinguishable from modern countries. I would go all the way to bigotry-blind but I feel like that would be doing something of a disservice to the history of hard-fought social progress within my world, but I do try to accommodate things like having a culturally accepted "third gender" and stuff like that, but it's something that ought to be handled with a lot of tact and often isn't.

I'd definitely be interested in hearing what PT nations and nations run by marginalized people have to say based on their experiences with the topic, as a non-disabled young cishet guy I know that I'm stumbling blindly in a lot of ways in that regard.

by Kiu Ghesik » Wed Apr 14, 2021 2:28 pm

New Anderia wrote:I'm not sure which is a bigger NS cliché, societies that are bigotry-blind or societies that turn the bigotry up to 11 (usually for no good reason). There are also ones that are pretty much indistinguishable from modern countries in terms of diversity (or lack thereof).

I'm personally grated much more by "hehe, [INSERT_X_RACIAL_OR_SEXUAL_MINORITY_HERE] go *boom*" than I am by societies being bigotry-blind. I mean, one is a matter of conservation of detail and another is just tactless. Here's an example: writing a bigotry-blind society is functionally indistinguishable from not touching on the matter, but, say, writing a trans woman being gunned down by people with AKs and police refusing to investigate in three sentences because it's edgy is just bluntly tasteless in my opinion. Something on the scale of Cassadia's "Political Activist" RP is practically the only way to do that sort of off-the-wall-bigotry society properly, because- like other forms of being edgy for the sake of being edgy- if done improperly it's a one-way trip to losing all the credibility a writer has.

New Anderia wrote:I'd definitely be interested in hearing what PT nations and nations run by marginalized people have to say based on their experiences with the topic, as a non-disabled young cishet guy I know that I'm stumbling blindly in a lot of ways in that regard.

I mean, apart from the "nomadic society with absolutely terrible population dynamics is fine with bisexuality and polygamy", it's... not good. I avoid touching on the issue, because, well... it's hard to write an incredibly insular society that disdains participating significantly in the slave trade on the grounds that "it's foreign" rather than any enlightenment sensibility in a way that doesn't come off as edgy to me as someone whose beliefs are informed by that enlightenment sensibility. To your point about "doing a disservice to history", that's fair- and why I don't write about it up front, since it's hard to explain to my readers in a satisfactory way the moral differences between societies. It does inform my writing, though, and I'd honestly suggest just keeping worldbuilding details like that behind the scenes unless you need to present them.

Conservation of detail can go a long way in that regard.

by South Reinkalistan » Wed Apr 14, 2021 2:43 pm

New Anderia wrote:I'm not sure which is a bigger NS cliché, societies that are bigotry-blind or societies that turn the bigotry up to 11 (usually for no good reason). There are also ones that are pretty much indistinguishable from modern countries in terms of diversity (or lack thereof).

I tend to want to go somewhere between bigotry-blind and indistinguishable from modern countries. I would go all the way to bigotry-blind but I feel like that would be doing something of a disservice to the history of hard-fought social progress within my world, but I do try to accommodate things like having a culturally accepted "third gender" and stuff like that, but it's something that ought to be handled with a lot of tact and often isn't.

I'd definitely be interested in hearing what PT nations and nations run by marginalized people have to say based on their experiences with the topic, as a non-disabled young cishet guy I know that I'm stumbling blindly in a lot of ways in that regard.

Heya. I don't think I'm specifically marginalised for any innate characteristics of mine but I'm of a certain category that people consider to be marginalised here so I'll give you some advice like you requested -- honestly I think you're kicking yourself when there's no real reason to. Just because you're young/cisgender/heterosexual doesn't mean you can't write about shit which you consider to be outside of your field of expertise. Instead, it's important just to do research by yourself on these things and try to come to your own conclusion. Everyone has biases on the issue, and I'm not gonna pretend I'm neutral.

My personal take on the cliche probably references my own beliefs or whatever, but I find social progress itself to be - while most certainly a thing - somewhat overstated in popular culture. Idk, having a society that's funny "haha X marginalised person go boom" as Kiu put it doesn't really grate me at all, because it sits on a real-world dichotomy. Sure it's done a lot of the time for edge's sake, but in the real world we have societies that are comically bigoted [a la, say, Putin's Russia in a lot of cases; even funnier the time that the DPRK news service literally dismissed a journalist reporting on them for being gay].

Really, I find societies with a mysterious lack of a culture war to be annoying. They're mostly the centre-right/libertarian self insert nations where gay people miraculously stop pride parading and there's miraculously no homophobia towards said gay people, or there's no discrimination on an ethnic basis because everyone's kept to themselves or whatever. If you run a moderately liberal society, or even just one that plays by contemporary global standards, there's gonna be a culture war or just a debate on those issues in general. I'm fine with horrifically bigoted societies if that's the case.

So yeah "bigotry-blind" societies are non-existent and that's fine. But there's not much wrong with really bigoted societies if they're done right/in a way that isn't stupidly edgy.

New Mexico and Northern Mexico + Hollywood Afghanistan; but it's surrounded by the evil magical empire led by the generic Dark Overlord, several generic "Medieval" kingdoms...and the advanced hidden elf village of 1930s L.A. Don't ask how I visualize these fever dreams. I don't either, sometimes.


New Anderia wrote:I'd definitely be interested in hearing what PT nations and nations run by marginalized people have to say based on their experiences with the topic, as a non-disabled young cishet guy I know that I'm stumbling blindly in a lot of ways in that regard.


It can get awkward, like KG said, it's best to avoid certain topics as intentional values dissonance flies over the head of a lot of readers. I've had somebody lecture me in a paragraph over why 13th Century peasants aren't enlightened, 'cause they valued replacement rates and found "permanent homosexual behavior" to be a corporal/humoral imbalance. Even if read between the lines, the implication was that "bisexuality" was the default sexuality prior to Christianity showing up.

The fact that the society I thought up has a female majority in sex ratio also leads to opposite assumptions. Before, quite a bit of readers assumed LP's old Cat Empire lived some kind of matriarchal paradise; where I (thought I) made it explicitly clear a monogamous and patriarchal majority made marriage (and several legal rights) illegal among peasants to strengthen their own grip on a centralized militaristic government or tolerated polygyny among the lower strata to keep the male registrars in an economic glass ceiling.

IIRC, some real life Southeast Asian "matriarchy" was created among similar lines.

by Yooper High Kingdom » Wed Apr 14, 2021 3:18 pm

New Anderia wrote:I'd definitely be interested in hearing what PT nations and nations run by marginalized people have to say based on their experiences with the topic, as a non-disabled young cishet guy I know that I'm stumbling blindly in a lot of ways in that regard.

Hi! PT nation here, plus a guy who runs a nation that takes place in Central America and another that is primarily inhabited by Native Americans. ( + Someone who IRL is often considered to be "not white", despite mostly Southern/Eastern Heritage, and is both Bisexual and Autistic. Gotta get my minority points™)

I don't understand what you are saying, but what I am getting from you is that a lot of nations either don't address bigotry or take it up to 11? Well, to put it quite frankly, I understand why some people might not find it important to address things like racism, sexism, bigotry, etc, or at the very least if they do it is in passing. Because, well, sometimes that just isn't important to the story. If you want to make a nation where such things are important subjects that you try to tackle in good faith, then go ahead. But I did not make Yooper in the hopes of addressing Homophobia and Sexism in 28th Century Finno-Norse Society. I did not make The Near Islands in the hope of drawing attention to the issues Native Americans face just for their birth. I did not make Republican Cabinda to address the horrors of being Black in a White Man's world (which is a major issue, even in the OTL). I just thought the ideas were cool. And for most of F7, that is the case. There are nations that take it up to 11 with their bigotry and, handled improperly, it can be offensive. Similarly, handwaving any and all social problems under the banner of "my ideology is the best and will solve all the problems" can be offensive if you make a nation for the sole purpose of displaying your ideology. But otherwise, we are here to worldbuild, not to address the issues with societies past, present, and future.

tl;dr: Sir, this is a Wendy's.

by Kyoki Chudoku » Wed Apr 14, 2021 4:27 pm

Diversity in general is a really strange topic when you think about it- ok, maybe it’s just me, but hear me out.

There’s a good number of nations that are developing effectively parallel with modernity. Nations that either are explicitly set in effectively the present or near-future and in which this present or near-future is effectively interchangeable with reality in terms of generally accepted values. So in these instances, a lot of the time issues that are ongoing in modernity tend to be addressed one way or another, and tend to have quite prominent importance- just see the number of MT nations with modern policies dedicated to, say, legalising gay marriage. There’s nothing wrong with that, but it reflects where these nations are coming from- they’re trying to address modern, present issues in the most direct way possible.

But a good deal of nations aren’t set in that kind of present. They’re in alternate histories clearly distinct from our own, or in a different time period all together, or in the far future or the distant past or in a fantasy world or trapped in the abyssal oceans of a spiralling rogue planet, and in these situations it’s actually somewhat more complicated. Not necessarily, I suppose- there’s plenty of idealistic future nations around portraying a personal utopia with unstoppable space fleets and the like- but if you’re, say, in PMT, different social issues are going to start cropping up. Transhumanism. Cybernetics. Virtual reality and the diminishment of what is real. You have to consider not only how existing prejudices shift, but how future ones will manifest. And if you have, say, an alien species, anything’s on the table. Sexism becomes a very different beast if you’re using the reproductive strategy of the angler-fish, or if everyone is an obligate hermaphrodite. Racism a different beast if one particular breed of the species is demonstrably superior in strength or intelligence or psionic potential. Sexuality completely different in a species that reproduces by budding, or where eusociality is in effect.

But such truly alien mindsets are the exception, I suppose. Diversity isn’t something I like addressing directly with my nations because it’s really not what they’re there for. I mean, Kyoki Chudoku is an oppressive tyrannical dictatorship. It’s not an actual place- the Chudokuren islands don’t exist anywhere in the real world- and though it’s got elements of Japanese culture thrown it, it’s not actually linked in any way to actual Japan. It’s in that weird zone of nations that speak the same language as real nations despite not actually being in a world where those nations actually exist. It doesn’t exist in the same history as reality, so it has different concepts of what current problems are. Sure, there’s some elements of say, racial bigotry- but the historical context is completely different. If you’re from Nakusika, you’re associated with a rebellion that resulted in biological weapons being unleashed. If you’re a neko and never got your features amputated, people are suspicious that you’re a tengokutankyu traitor. Kyoki Chudoku isn’t about bigotry- it’s about me deciding to make a magical insane tyrannical dystopia. So the elements of bigotry that do exist are more just an incidental result of the nation’s history. Kyoki Chudoku is hardly the best structured nation, or one intending to be very true to life, but I’m using it as an example because it shows the sort of fundamental problems I at least have with addressing these aspects of a country.

There’s obviously some people who delve into these issues with all the tact of a nuclear explosion. There’s some people who centralise their nation around a debate of personal interest to them, really delving into the intricacies of it. Most nations, though, don’t exist in that capacity- not around particular modern societal issues, anyway. Diversity and bigotry are strange because they’re such general terms and yet tend to have that particular association with how we understand them today, at this very time. Personally, I find a lot more interest in more obscure or crazy issues. Debates over the morality of magical technology, a civilisation centred around the inevitably of dying out within a few generations, a civil war between psychopathic lunatics and their extremist interpretations of a tyrant’s self-justifications for oppressing and tormenting the populace- these might not be present issues, or real issues, or really issues at all more like societal contexts, but they’re fun for me to explore.

...so I just wrote all that and I don’t quite know what the point I was actually making was, but I’ve written too much to not post it now. Consider it my overly convoluted reflection on the subject.
This nation exists for fun and insanity, not to represent my actual views which are much more mundane and boring.
Also, I don't use NS stats. So please ignore them.

by New Anderia » Wed Apr 14, 2021 5:03 pm

Yooper High Kingdom wrote:I don't understand what you are saying, but what I am getting from you is that a lot of nations either don't address bigotry or take it up to 11? Well, to put it quite frankly, I understand why some people might not find it important to address things like racism, sexism, bigotry, etc, or at the very least if they do it is in passing. Because, well, sometimes that just isn't important to the story.
But otherwise, we are here to worldbuild, not to address the issues with societies past, present, and future.
tl;dr: Sir, this is a Wendy's.


What I'm saying is that, part of worldbuilding inherently includes the society that is being built. Generally speaking, that's probably going to include to some extent the prejudices of that society. I'm definitely NOT saying that people have to address them, I personally prefer to do as Kiu Ghesik suggested, which is conservation of detail in regards to that. It should also be noted that not everyone's worldbuilding has a separate story—for me, the worldbuilding *is* the story. Building off of what Kyoki Chudoku was saying also, these prejudices aren't automatically going to be the same ones we have in the real world.

I also find the implication that including these issues in any capacity obligates you to center them or that addressing the flaws of a built society is counter to or outside of the "point" of worldbuilding to be somewhat distasteful.
